<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910705-0114</DOCNO><DOCID>910705-0114.</DOCID><HL>   Bank Deposit Rates   To Be Cut in Japan   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>07/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)</IN><NS>INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND ANALYSIS (IEN)</NS><RE>FAR EAST (FE)JAPAN (JA)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)</RE><LP>   TOKYO -- Japan will lower regulated bank-deposit rates 33basis points, the Finance Ministry said. A basis point is ahundredth of a percentage point.   The reduction in the eight different rates is scheduled totake effect July 29. Commercial banks were waiting to see thesize of the cut before deciding whether to lower theirshort-term prime rates, some bankers said.</LP><TEXT>   The Finance Ministry and the Bank of Japan set many of therates on small bank deposits following moves in the discountrate. The Bank of Japan on Monday lowered the discount rateto 5 1/2% from 6%.   About 30% of the funds that commercial banks gather comewith regulated interest rates, so banks were waiting to seethe range of the cut in those deposit rates beforeconsidering lowering their own short-term prime rate, bankerssaid. With the roughly 25 basis point decline in rates forbenchmark unregulated deposits, banks are considering cuttingtheir short-term prime rates to as low as 7 1/2% from 7 7/8%.   The short-term prime is the charge levied by commercialbanks on loans of a year or less and is the benchmark for thelong-term prime rate. The commercial banks set theirlong-term prime 30 or 50 basis points above the short prime,depending on the term of the loan.   The rate on three-month regulated deposits will be 3 3/4%,down from 4.08%. Rates on new three-month certificates ofdeposit, a benchmark in the money market and an indication ofthe cost of funds for banks, are around 7.63%, down from 7.9%at the end of last week.   Rates on postal system savings deposits will also be cut,depending on the type of deposit.</TEXT></DOC>